params._modules: List of modules to enable. All modules must be approved by the Controller
params._units: List of units. Each unit is the # of components per 10^18 of a JPToken

decimals().details: Returns the number of decimals used to get its user representation. For example, if `decimals` equals `2`, a balance of `505` tokens should be displayed to a user as `5,05` (`505 / 10 ** 2`). Tokens usually opt for a value of 18, imitating the relationship between Ether and Wei. This is the value {ERC20} uses, unless {_setupDecimals} is called. NOTE: This information is only used for _display_ purposes: it in no way affects any of the arithmetic of the contract, including {IERC20-balanceOf} and {IERC20-transfer}.

decreaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically decreases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address. - `spender` must have allowance for the caller of at least `subtractedValue`.

increaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically increases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

params._target: Address of the smart contract to call
params._value: Quantity of Ether to provide the call (typically 0)

name().details: Returns the name of the token.

symbol().details: Returns the symbol of the token, usually a shorter version of the name.

transfer(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transfer}. Requirements: - `recipient` cannot be the zero address. - the caller must have a balance of at least `amount`.

transferFrom(address,address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transferFrom}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. This is not required by the EIP. See the note at the beginning of {ERC20}; Requirements: - `sender` and `recipient` cannot be the zero address. - `sender` must have a balance of at least `amount`. - the caller must have allowance for ``sender``'s tokens of at least `amount`.

addComponent(address).notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. Low level function that adds a component to the components array.

addExternalPositionModule(address,addres.notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. Low level function that adds a module to a component's externalPositionModules array

addModule(address).notice: MANAGER ONLY. Adds a module into a PENDING state; Module must later be initialized via  module's initialize function

burn(address,uint256).notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. Decreases the "account" balance by the "quantity". _burn checks that the "account" already has the required "quantity".

methods.constructor: When a new JPToken is created, initializes Positions in default state and adds modules into pending state. All parameter validations are on the JPTokenCreator contract. Validations are performed already on the  JPTokenCreator. Initiates the positionMultiplier as 1e18 (no adjustments).

editDefaultPositionUnit(address,int256).notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. Low level function that edits a component's virtual unit. Takes a real unit and converts it to virtual before committing.

editExternalPositionData(address,address.notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. Low level function that edits a component's external position data

editExternalPositionUnit(address,address.notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. Low level function that edits a component's external position virtual unit.  Takes a real unit and converts it to virtual before committing.

editPositionMultiplier(int256).notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. Modifies the position multiplier. This is typically used to efficiently update all the Positions' units at once in applications where inflation is awarded (e.g. subscription fees).

getPositions().notice: Returns a list of Positions, through traversing the components. Each component with a non-zero virtual unit is considered a Default Position, and each externalPositionModule will generate a unique position. Virtual units are converted to real units. This function is typically used off-chain for data presentation purposes.

getTotalComponentRealUnits(address).notice: Returns the total Real Units for a given component, summing the default and external position units.

initializeModule().notice: Initializes an added module from PENDING to INITIALIZED state. Can only call when unlocked. An address can only enter a PENDING state if it is an enabled module added by the manager. Only callable by the module itself, hence msg.sender is the subject of update.

invoke(address,uint256,bytes).notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. Low level function that allows a module to make an arbitrary function call to any contract.

isInitializedModule(address).notice: Only ModuleStates of INITIALIZED modules are considered enabled

isPendingModule(address).notice: Returns whether the module is in a pending state

lock().notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. When a JPToken is locked, only the locker can call privileged functions.

mint(address,uint256).notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. Increases the "account" balance by the "quantity".

removeComponent(address).notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. Low level function that removes a component from the components array.

removeExternalPositionModule(address,add.notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. Low level function that removes a module from a component's  externalPositionModules array and deletes the associated externalPosition.

removeModule(address).notice: MANAGER ONLY. Removes a module from the JPToken. JPToken calls removeModule on module itself to confirm it is not needed to manage any remaining positions and to remove state.

removePendingModule(address).notice: MANAGER ONLY. Removes a pending module from the JPToken.

setManager(address).notice: MANAGER ONLY. Changes manager; We allow null addresses in case the manager wishes to wind down the JPToken. Modules may rely on the manager state, so only changable when unlocked

unlock().notice: PRIVELEGED MODULE FUNCTION. Unlocks the JPToken and clears the locker
